nib.text:
A fire spread within a Catholic church in southwest Minneapolis early Wednesday.

At about 3:42 a.m., firefighters responded to the 3800 block of Pleasant Avenue S for a fire at Incarnation Catholic Church.

Upon arrival, crews observed fire on the first floor and the roof of the building. 

By about 4 a.m., firefighters had put out most of the fire while continuing to ventilate the smoke-filled building and checking around for places where the fire might have spread. At 5 a.m., firefighters declared the fire extinguished.

The extent of damage was not available but reports said the fire was contained without spreading beyond the sanctuary and roof directly above it.

No injuries were reported, and reports citing officials said no one was inside when firefighters arrived.

A [report](https://thecatholicspirit.com/news/local-news/early-morning-fire-damages-incarnation-in-south-minneapolis-march-9/) citing Incarnations pastor Father Kevin McDonough said "it was about as good a result as a bad fire can produce. The direct damage was confined to one side of the chapel (although there is smoke damage everywhere). Minneapolis Fire Department did a great job of putting the fire out.

 The church was built in 1911, according to its [website](https://www.incarnationmpls.org/).

The cause of the fire is under investigation.
